ores the prevalent images, ideologies, social myths, and attitudes of late Meiji and Early Taisho Japan. Her lively narrative draws on guide books, magazines, success literature, and popular novels to illuminate the formation of ideas about work, class, gender relations, and freedom in American society. This study analyzes the Japanese construction of a mythic America, perceived as a homogeneous and exotic "other."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aImmigrantszNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistory. 0aJapanese American menzNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistory. 0aJapanese AmericanszNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistory. 4aUSA. 4aethnic studies. 4ahistory of migration. 4ahistory. 4aideologies. 4aimmigration. 4aliberty. 4amigrants. 4amigration. 4aminorities. 4apolitics. 4aregional history. 4asocial history. 4awork. 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052033769540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520337701?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520337701423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520337701/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles